05:21.029 --> 05:22.530
MEGAN: Hey.
-Hi.

05:23.740 --> 05:25.825
Finally figured it out.

05:25.908 --> 05:28.119
My muffin recipe?

05:28.202 --> 05:31.080
-No, that's always gonna stay a secret.
-That's true.

05:31.164 --> 05:33.374
-What I wanna do.
-What?

05:33.458 --> 05:36.502
-I'm gonna paint again, Nell.
-Megan.

05:36.586 --> 05:39.380
What's it been? Almost 18 years now

05:39.464 --> 05:42.091
that you've helped other artists' dreams come true.

05:42.175 --> 05:45.845
And now you're inspired, finally,
to do it for yourself?

05:45.928 --> 05:48.014
-It's about time.
-I think so too.

05:48.097 --> 05:50.767
Oh-oh. Look who just emerged
from their dungeon.

05:50.850 --> 05:52.643
-Temporary furlough.
NELL: Oh.

05:53.519 --> 05:55.188
Is there anything we can do to help?

05:55.271 --> 05:57.440
I'm not sure there's anything anyone can do.

05:57.940 --> 06:00.818
-Well, I'm here if you need me.
-Thank you.

06:01.486 --> 06:02.820
And, Mick...

06:05.698 --> 06:08.159
I've decided I'm going to paint.

06:08.242 --> 06:10.787
I'm gonna set up the studio
and just see what I can do.

06:10.870 --> 06:12.997
[♪♪♪]

06:18.544 --> 06:21.172
Well, that's great, Megan. I'm proud of you.

06:24.217 --> 06:27.553
ABBY: Connor, you're early.
-Looks like I'm right on time.

06:27.637 --> 06:29.097
You cannot eat that.

06:29.180 --> 06:32.308
Oh, Abby, you're not gonna be able
to eat both, trust me.

06:32.391 --> 06:33.351
What's this?

06:33.434 --> 06:34.852
Indexed and cataloged,

06:34.936 --> 06:36.687
local Maryland and Supreme Court rulings

06:36.771 --> 06:39.107
on whistle-blowing and whistle-blowers,

06:39.190 --> 06:42.110
with relevant facts, circumstances
and aspects of the law

06:42.193 --> 06:43.778
with particular relevance.

06:43.861 --> 06:44.862
Wow.

06:45.863 --> 06:48.074
Thank you. You did not have to do that.

06:48.157 --> 06:51.786
Don't worry about that. I kind of enjoyed it.

06:51.869 --> 06:54.497
-You enjoy research?
-Okay, not really.

06:54.580 --> 06:56.332
But I enjoyed the change.

06:56.958 --> 06:58.918
Uncle Thomas is gearing up for the Hubert case,

06:59.001 --> 07:00.378
a huge trial in New York,

07:00.461 --> 07:05.133
and I have been and will be glued
to my computer doing more research.

07:05.216 --> 07:08.052
Well, I'm glad my life is entertaining to you.

07:08.136 --> 07:09.512
Seriously, you can't eat that.

07:09.595 --> 07:11.639
I don't mind butter on my pancakes anymore.

07:12.181 --> 07:14.809
So... Mom and Dad.

07:16.185 --> 07:19.397
-Huh. Really? I thought you'd be upset.
-Upset?

07:19.897 --> 07:21.983
They wanna try again after all this time?

07:22.066 --> 07:24.235
-That takes insane bravery.
-Or just insanity.

07:24.318 --> 07:28.698
-What, you don't approve?
-Mm. No, quite the opposite. I mean...

07:30.366 --> 07:32.827
to be able to forgive after everything?

07:32.910 --> 07:33.744
Yeah.

07:34.996 --> 07:38.708
-Guess you gotta go after what you want.
-Like eating my breakfast?

07:39.542 --> 07:42.628
Oh. Jay, good to see you.

07:42.712 --> 07:45.006
Sorry. Do you want me to order another...?

07:45.089 --> 07:48.050
No, I'm good.
Sally's serves too much food anyways.

07:48.134 --> 07:50.136
That's very true. Uh, I'll see you later?

07:50.595 --> 07:52.096
-Thank you.
CONNOR: Of course.

07:52.180 --> 07:53.556
-See you, Jay. Yeah.
-Later.

07:55.183 --> 07:56.726
[MOUTHS]
<i>I like him.</i>

07:56.809 --> 07:59.270
So did I get the thumbs up or down?

07:59.353 --> 08:01.355
-Does it matter?
-With your family, yeah.

08:01.439 --> 08:04.901
-Yeah, I think it matters a lot.
-Well, it was a thumbs up.

08:04.984 --> 08:06.777
-Great.
-Do you want some of my pancakes?

08:06.861 --> 08:09.155
No, no, I'm good, thank you. I'm fine, yeah.

08:09.822 --> 08:12.116
Oh, the toast and eggs look untouched.

08:12.200 --> 08:13.743
Nothing really bothers you, does it?

08:15.495 --> 08:18.289
I mean, did you learn that
from teaching third grade?

08:18.372 --> 08:20.124
Uh, no, no.

08:20.208 --> 08:23.794
Actually, learning that led me
to teaching third grade.

08:24.879 --> 08:28.716
I was working on my master's
in marine biology at Woods Hole,

08:28.799 --> 08:30.968
spending most of my time on offshore trawlers,

08:31.052 --> 08:33.638
analyzing Atlantic mackerel populations,

08:33.721 --> 08:37.350
when I just-- I finally decided to switch careers.

08:37.850 --> 08:40.977
-Give up counting fish?
-Shocking, I know.

08:41.854 --> 08:45.107
No, I thought of the lives of the people
who mattered most to me,

08:45.191 --> 08:48.486
besides my family, and they were all teachers.

08:49.904 --> 08:54.075
And I realized that life wasn't supposed
to go in a straight line.

08:54.784 --> 08:58.079
And that if I wanted to turn, I could just do it, turn.

08:58.996 --> 08:59.914
Wow.

08:59.997 --> 09:02.416
[♪♪♪]

09:02.500 --> 09:05.127
I can't imagine giving up something
I've wanted my whole life.

09:05.795 --> 09:09.507
Well, for me, it was realizing
that I wanted a lot of things in life,

09:09.590 --> 09:11.509
and it was just merely a matter of choosing what.

09:13.427 --> 09:17.932
-Do you ever regret it?
-Only when people eat my breakfast.

09:18.015 --> 09:19.559
[JAY LAUGHS]

09:22.186 --> 09:24.063
Hey, do you want some company today?

09:24.146 --> 09:28.484
-What? During my deposition?
-Well, not during, that would be awkward.

09:28.568 --> 09:29.777
I was thinking after.

09:30.820 --> 09:33.281
-Don't you have to prep for prep day?
-Yes, I do.

09:33.364 --> 09:36.993
But I have a feeling you're gonna need
a juice box when you're done.

09:38.119 --> 09:39.203
[JAY CHUCKLES]

09:39.287 --> 09:40.496
All right, I'm gonna dig in.

09:43.833 --> 09:46.919
[IN ENGLISH ACCENT] Still think about it.
That, and football. Quarterback.

09:48.004 --> 09:51.382
[IN NORMAL VOICE]
So you're a failed rock-star quarterback

09:51.465 --> 09:56.470
that can't eat fish.

09:56.554 --> 10:01.183
-Deep into previews and still rewriting?
-Yep, it can always be better.

10:01.267 --> 10:03.936
Last night, it seemed
the audience wanted a button on the scene.

10:04.020 --> 10:06.522
-I kind of like the callback to act one.
-Yeah, I like it too.

10:06.606 --> 10:09.567
Have you given any thought
to your other writing assignment?

10:09.650 --> 10:10.985
My other what?

10:11.068 --> 10:12.111
[♪♪♪]

10:12.194 --> 10:15.573
The note from the playwright? For the program?

10:15.656 --> 10:17.450
I haven't given it any thought.

10:18.576 --> 10:21.245
Well, considering you're a best-selling novelist,

10:21.329 --> 10:24.248
people are going to expect something impressive.

10:24.332 --> 10:27.209
-No pressure.
-I'm sure it'll be great.

10:27.293 --> 10:29.795
-So a little pressure?
-Just a little.

10:29.879 --> 10:32.006
So I'll see you this afternoon at our Q&A?

10:32.089 --> 10:33.591
Yep, can't wait.

10:33.674 --> 10:35.468
Oh!

10:35.551 --> 10:36.886
And I'd add "tone deaf."

10:36.969 --> 10:38.346
[♪♪♪]

10:38.429 --> 10:42.016
"So you're a tone-deaf,
failed rock-star quarterback."

10:42.099 --> 10:45.227
If you're gonna go for the callback,
you might as well go all the way.

10:45.311 --> 10:46.562
I love you.

10:50.983 --> 10:52.193
[♪♪♪]

10:53.319 --> 10:56.447
SARAH: Oh, no, what's the score?
CARRIE: We're up, 19-3.

10:56.530 --> 10:58.115
-Hey.
GIRLS: Uncle Connor!

10:58.199 --> 11:00.868
I heard Nana has lunch inside.
Come on, I'll race you!

11:00.951 --> 11:01.911
Yay!

11:01.994 --> 11:05.456
KEVIN: You know, pretty soon,
we will be doing this with our own kids.

11:05.539 --> 11:07.333
So how many?

11:07.416 --> 11:09.835
I was thinking football team?

11:09.919 --> 11:13.464
-Wow. Okay, that is a lot of O'Briens.
-Yeah.

11:13.547 --> 11:15.549
You know, we never really talked about numbers.

11:15.633 --> 11:17.676
There's a lot of things that we need to talk about.

11:17.760 --> 11:20.429
[♪♪♪]

11:20.513 --> 11:23.224
-This is the opposite of talking.
-We'll get there.

11:23.307 --> 11:24.475
[SARAH CHUCKLES]

11:25.059 --> 11:26.435
A whole football team?

11:27.937 --> 11:29.313
Maybe just the offense.

11:36.320 --> 11:37.154
You busy?

11:39.281 --> 11:42.243
No. I'm just, uh, running the numbers.

11:43.661 --> 11:45.037
I was hoping we could talk.

11:48.416 --> 11:51.460
I know you're still upset about me
not telling you what Mark Hall said.

11:51.544 --> 11:53.838
I just don't like being left in the dark.

11:53.921 --> 11:57.341
-And how do I know you weren't considering it?
-I told him no, Trace.

11:59.135 --> 12:00.052
I know you did.

12:00.136 --> 12:03.013
I wasn't gonna let him use me
to get you back on tour.

12:04.390 --> 12:07.226
I'm sorry. I thought you were hiding it from me.

12:07.893 --> 12:11.021
When you've been in the business this long,
you don't know who to trust.

12:13.149 --> 12:14.316
Trace...

12:15.359 --> 12:19.780
it's not every day you meet someone
who makes you feel safe

12:20.406 --> 12:21.949
and believes in you,

12:22.032 --> 12:24.368
but doesn't wanna take away who you are.

12:27.288 --> 12:30.499
You're different. Different from what I know.

12:31.876 --> 12:32.877
And I like that.

12:33.502 --> 12:35.337
[♪♪♪]

12:36.505 --> 12:37.590
I like you.

12:40.509 --> 12:41.343
[CLEARS THROAT]

12:44.722 --> 12:45.681
Now look who's hiding.

12:47.308 --> 12:49.852
I'm not exactly hiding, it's just...

12:52.354 --> 12:54.773
I was thinking about grabbing some lunch.

12:56.692 --> 13:01.197
-You wanna join me?
-Yeah, I'd like that.

13:01.280 --> 13:02.156
All right.

13:05.034 --> 13:07.536
[♪♪♪]

13:07.620 --> 13:10.456
-Okay, thank you.
-Tell me you have good news.

13:10.539 --> 13:13.417
The power company is sending
somebody out this afternoon.

13:13.501 --> 13:15.711
This afternoon? I thought you were gonna fix it.

13:15.794 --> 13:20.132
No. Last time I tried to mess with electricity,
I blew out my parents' Christmas lights.

13:20.216 --> 13:22.635
-Well, that's not that bad.
-I set the lawn on fire.

13:22.718 --> 13:24.386
Oh, yeah. That's bad.

13:24.470 --> 13:25.513
[DOORBELL RINGS]

13:25.596 --> 13:27.806
-Power company, maybe?
-Maybe.

13:32.770 --> 13:34.939
-Hi.
-We're here to check in.

13:35.022 --> 13:36.982
What? Now?

13:37.066 --> 13:39.443
WOMAN: Hi, nice place.
MAN: Hi there.

13:40.444 --> 13:41.529
WOMAN: Hello.
MAN: Look at this.

13:41.612 --> 13:43.697
-Uh-oh.
-Uh-oh?

13:44.156 --> 13:46.700
-This says we're open.
-That kind of "uh-oh."

13:46.784 --> 13:49.245
We're not supposed to open till next week.
We have no food.

13:49.328 --> 13:51.872
-Or electricity.
-The mattresses haven't been delivered.

13:51.956 --> 13:54.041
-So we're a B and B...
-Without the B or the B.

13:55.084 --> 13:56.752
[HUMMING]

13:56.835 --> 13:58.837
[♪♪♪]

14:05.219 --> 14:08.722
[IN PIRATE VOICE]
Admiral? What course shall we be taking?

14:08.806 --> 14:12.643
It be morning soon,
so we point the bow toward the rising sun.

14:12.726 --> 14:15.563
Aye, aye, admiral, but what if there not be land?

14:15.646 --> 14:17.398
Yes. What if...?

14:18.732 --> 14:21.235
[IN NORMAL VOICE]
Hey, what's a pirate's favorite letter?

14:21.318 --> 14:23.070
-R!
-R!

14:23.153 --> 14:25.906
[IN PIRATE VOICE]
You'd think it be R, but it is the C.

14:25.990 --> 14:30.202
-Time for this one to be walking the plank!
-That's not in the script-- Ha-ha!

14:30.286 --> 14:33.414
I'll sign the documents, but I haven't read them yet.

14:34.290 --> 14:35.749
Listen, I can't delegate,

14:35.833 --> 14:38.836
and I can't just give up everything else
I've got going on right now.

14:38.919 --> 14:40.754
All right, okay. Thanks.

14:40.838 --> 14:42.089
-Hey, Grandpa.
-Yeah?

14:42.172 --> 14:43.674
Do you wanna practice with us?

14:43.757 --> 14:46.719
You know what, honey?
I think that might be just one admiral too many.

14:46.802 --> 14:50.723
And besides, uh, today I have to be a landlubber.

14:50.806 --> 14:52.474
But thanks, Caitlyn. Appreciate it.

14:52.558 --> 14:53.517
Arg.

14:54.268 --> 14:57.479
Why don't I meet you on the upper deck,
and I'm gonna go talk to Grandpa?

14:57.563 --> 14:59.064
-Okay.
-Okay. Race there.

14:59.148 --> 15:00.816
-Hey, Dad?
MICK: Yeah?

15:00.900 --> 15:02.276
CONNOR:
Um, listen.

15:02.359 --> 15:03.360
CAITLYN:
Let's do this.

15:03.444 --> 15:05.195
I was wondering...

15:05.279 --> 15:07.740
with everything going on with Dilpher,
um, do you need any help?

15:08.157 --> 15:10.993
Oh, you know, I know you're busy, but thank you.

15:11.076 --> 15:13.746
No, I am, but, uh, I mean it.

15:13.829 --> 15:15.581
No, that's okay, Connor.

15:15.664 --> 15:18.083
I've got it under control, but thanks.

15:19.376 --> 15:20.210
Okay.

15:20.294 --> 15:22.296
[♪♪♪]

15:26.133 --> 15:28.802
-Hey. I'm here for oregano and Dad.
-Hi.

15:28.886 --> 15:31.096
Oregano, no idea. Dad, in his office.

15:31.180 --> 15:32.014
Got it.

15:33.766 --> 15:34.683
Hey, Dad.

15:34.767 --> 15:37.770
Hey, you must be excited
about the inn opening soon.

15:37.853 --> 15:41.440
It's already open,
just without the beds or the breakfasts.

15:41.523 --> 15:43.567
-So that's going great.
-Oh, good.

15:43.651 --> 15:46.028
-Anything I can do?
-Do you have time to make beds?

15:46.111 --> 15:48.113
Not really, but I thought I should just ask.

15:48.197 --> 15:52.451
Thanks. So, um...

15:52.534 --> 15:53.369
you and Mom?

15:53.452 --> 15:54.745
[♪♪♪]

15:55.204 --> 15:56.372
What's going on there?

15:57.539 --> 15:58.707
[STAMMERS]

15:58.791 --> 16:02.628
We're just, you know,
I guess, uh, taking it slow, you know?

16:02.711 --> 16:03.587
Step by step.

16:04.588 --> 16:07.341
Good. So baby steps?

16:08.550 --> 16:09.551
Yeah, baby steps.

16:10.844 --> 16:13.681
Okay. Thank you.

16:15.683 --> 16:17.518
MEGAN:
My spare bedroom's gonna be perfect.

16:17.601 --> 16:19.812
With the northern light coming
through those windows?

16:19.895 --> 16:22.731
You need to get Mick to help you with the studio.

16:24.608 --> 16:26.902
Nah. He's too busy. I'm not gonna ask him.

16:26.986 --> 16:29.905
-Well... Oh.
-So, what do you think of this?

16:29.989 --> 16:33.492
It's perfect. It's almost exactly
like the studio I used to have.

16:33.575 --> 16:35.369
-That one's great.
-Mm.

16:35.452 --> 16:37.454
But you need Mick to help you.

16:37.538 --> 16:39.415
-Let him.
-Ugh.

16:41.709 --> 16:42.835
Maybe I should.

16:42.918 --> 16:45.129
We didn't talk enough when we were married,

16:45.838 --> 16:47.131
and that was a mistake.

16:47.214 --> 16:49.633
Darling, you two since then have learned a lot.

16:49.717 --> 16:51.677
Hope we've learned enough.

16:52.928 --> 16:54.388
Pie looks too good. I'm leaving.

16:54.471 --> 16:56.098
[BOTH LAUGH]

16:57.099 --> 16:58.517
MEGAN:
Hey, Trace!

16:59.268 --> 17:00.519
Megan. Hey.

17:02.021 --> 17:05.523
Oh, this is, uh, Emma. She works at the Bridge.

17:05.607 --> 17:08.027
Hello, Emma. Hope he's not working you too hard.

17:08.109 --> 17:10.612
As bosses go, he's okay.

17:10.695 --> 17:13.323
Well, as carpenters go, he's amazing.

17:13.406 --> 17:15.576
I love what you did for the set for the school play.

17:15.659 --> 17:16.910
Thanks.

17:16.993 --> 17:19.704
MEGAN: Have you seen them?
-I'd love to take a tour.

17:20.372 --> 17:23.333
If you're gonna do it, you better hurry,
tonight is closing night.

17:23.416 --> 17:25.752
I'll see if my boss will give me a night off.

17:26.420 --> 17:29.089
We should probably, uh, get inside and order.

17:29.173 --> 17:31.216
-But it's good to see you, Megan.
-Yeah. You too.

17:33.302 --> 17:34.595
EMMA: Bye.
-Bye.

17:42.436 --> 17:46.648
I don't know. It's kind of weird.
We've talked about our lives together.

17:46.732 --> 17:49.193
But we may have neglected some of the details.

17:49.276 --> 17:50.319
Hmm.

17:50.402 --> 17:53.697
Oh. You didn't tell her
about the football team, did you?

17:53.781 --> 17:54.990
-Just the offense.
-Oh!

17:55.074 --> 17:57.367
O'Brien runs for the foul line.

17:57.451 --> 18:00.913
She passes, and it's a three-point shot
for an O'Brien hat trick!

18:00.996 --> 18:03.957
-Nope, none of that was right.
-Ah!

18:04.041 --> 18:07.211
-Have you seen sports?
-What? Those were all sports words.

18:07.294 --> 18:10.506
Anyways, I just feel like we went

18:10.589 --> 18:12.716
from being engaged to married in just three weeks,

18:12.800 --> 18:16.762
and we may have skipped a few conversations.

18:17.930 --> 18:18.847
Hm.

18:20.224 --> 18:23.602
-At least now you have a lot of time to talk about it.
-That's true.

18:24.895 --> 18:25.896
[KEVIN CHUCKLES]

18:26.814 --> 18:29.316
What about you?
How are you doing with everything?

18:32.402 --> 18:33.237
Well...

18:34.738 --> 18:39.368
my novel just broke top 10
and I have a play opening this week.

18:40.160 --> 18:41.328
-Wow.
-Yeah.

18:41.411 --> 18:43.330
-Congratulations, Bree, really.
-Thank you.

18:43.413 --> 18:46.458
Just hope I can figure out what to write
for this playbill thingy.

18:46.542 --> 18:48.418
It's easier to write about other people.

18:48.502 --> 18:50.587
Really? Don't you always write about yourself?

18:50.671 --> 18:54.133
No, I write about the fictional me, not the real me.

18:54.216 --> 18:56.301
The fictional me has it all figured out.

18:56.385 --> 18:58.387
-Thank you for watching the store.
-Yeah.

18:58.470 --> 19:00.806
And don't put anything on sale while I'm gone.

19:02.057 --> 19:03.183
Full price.

19:06.103 --> 19:06.979
TRACE:
Mm.

19:07.062 --> 19:10.023
The hardest part's always loading up after a show.

19:10.107 --> 19:14.236
Three o'clock in the morning
in some one-traffic-light town.

19:14.319 --> 19:16.989
A bad night's sleep on an old motel mattress,

19:17.072 --> 19:19.992
listening to a rattling air conditioner. Heh.

19:20.075 --> 19:23.871
Knowing you got eight hours behind the wheel
so you can do it again.

19:23.954 --> 19:26.832
That sounds tough. And lonely.

19:28.500 --> 19:31.086
Yeah. And no.

19:31.170 --> 19:32.838
At least the hotels get better, right?

19:33.338 --> 19:36.008
If it's not where you wanna be, it's just four walls.

19:37.009 --> 19:41.680
Yeah. You know,
you're really not selling me on the road.

19:41.763 --> 19:45.058
Well, that's the thing. I've had some
of the best times of my life on the road.

19:45.726 --> 19:47.686
Your band becomes your family.

19:47.769 --> 19:52.232
I love John and Leigh,
and I always will, but it ain't easy.

19:55.277 --> 19:56.820
You gotta really want it.

19:58.530 --> 20:00.657
It's not easy leaving the people you love.

20:01.491 --> 20:03.493
[♪♪♪]

20:05.245 --> 20:06.955
Yeah, I know.

20:12.669 --> 20:13.754
WOMAN:
<i>Ms. O'Brien.</i>

20:14.296 --> 20:18.091
Are you denying that you released
my client's proprietary data?

20:19.259 --> 20:22.346
When you say "propriety data," are you referring to

20:22.429 --> 20:24.598
the illegal activities of the Porter Fund?

20:24.681 --> 20:27.184
Alleged illegal activity, and you're being evasive.

20:27.267 --> 20:28.644
Well, alleged or not,

20:28.727 --> 20:31.146
there was enough information
to open a federal investigation.

20:32.814 --> 20:36.777
You were recently suspended
by Capital Management. Why was that?

20:37.778 --> 20:40.280
-It's an internal matter.
-Which we can subpoena.

20:40.364 --> 20:44.076
And they will fight
because that is also proprietary information.

20:48.580 --> 20:51.333
Abby, we don't want you.

20:52.417 --> 20:54.169
But someone has to pay.

20:54.836 --> 20:56.922
You give up Capital Management,

20:57.005 --> 20:58.715
and in two months' time,

20:58.799 --> 21:04.388
Hunter Drew & Associates will offer you
a VP position with a 20-percent raise.

21:06.306 --> 21:09.893
-So you're bribing me?
-We're offering you an alternative.

21:12.896 --> 21:14.690
You know, ahem...

21:14.773 --> 21:16.525
since I was suspended,

21:16.608 --> 21:19.444
I have done cleanup duty at my daughters' school.

21:19.528 --> 21:21.196
I'm producing their school play,

21:21.280 --> 21:23.282
I've taken them to gymnastics four times a week,

21:23.365 --> 21:25.409
and I've tucked them into bed every single night.

21:25.492 --> 21:28.620
That's heartwarming.
But I don't think you understand.

21:29.288 --> 21:31.581
This is the best offer you're going to get.

21:31.665 --> 21:35.085
And if you don't take it,
we're going to keep coming after you.

21:37.713 --> 21:39.881
You know, I don't think you understand.

21:39.965 --> 21:41.425
[♪♪♪]

21:41.508 --> 21:45.137
If I don't teach my children
to stand up for what's right,

21:45.220 --> 21:49.266
regardless of the consequences, then I've failed.

21:49.349 --> 21:53.061
And, to me, that is more important
than anything you can threaten me with.

21:53.145 --> 21:56.273
So... I think we're done here.

22:00.277 --> 22:02.279
[♪♪♪]

22:02.362 --> 22:05.073
And as much as I love New York,

22:05.157 --> 22:08.410
you know, I realized
that true theater can be staged anywhere.

22:08.493 --> 22:09.661
BREE: Hm.
-Mm-hm.

22:10.871 --> 22:12.414
Next question.

22:12.497 --> 22:14.333
So, Bree, where do you get your inspiration?

22:14.416 --> 22:19.004
Okay, inspiration. I would love to say
that it all comes from my imagination,

22:19.087 --> 22:20.339
but that is not the case.

22:20.422 --> 22:23.592
I think between my plays and my book,

22:23.675 --> 22:26.928
most of my inspiration comes
from the people that are closest to me.

22:27.345 --> 22:30.724
My friends, my family, whether they like it or not.

22:30.807 --> 22:33.268
Wait, is your book based on your family?

22:33.351 --> 22:36.104
[♪♪♪]

22:36.188 --> 22:38.190
I mean, with the...

22:38.273 --> 22:40.734
-Mmm. Not--
-Let's jump to another question.

22:40.817 --> 22:43.820
-That's a good idea.
-You, right there. Have a question?

22:44.738 --> 22:48.075
If we don't get the power back soon,
you can call me Laura Ingalls

22:48.158 --> 22:50.535
because this is <i>Little House</i>
<i>on the Chesapeake Shore.</i>

22:50.619 --> 22:52.079
The electrician couldn't fix it?

22:52.162 --> 22:55.415
He said something
about corroded something or other,

22:55.499 --> 22:58.043
or faulty neutral-wire thingies.

22:58.126 --> 22:59.753
Are you sure he was an electrician?

22:59.836 --> 23:02.839
Well, I'm paraphrasing because I'm upset.

23:02.923 --> 23:05.675
-About your parents?
-Well, kind of, but no.

23:05.759 --> 23:09.387
I'm upset because this is not
how this was supposed to go.

23:09.471 --> 23:11.473
-We're supposed to have beds.
-And power.

23:11.556 --> 23:13.517
Yeah. That too.

23:13.600 --> 23:15.936
At least your apartment still has electricity.

23:16.019 --> 23:18.396
-It's like you live in the future.
-Don't worry.

23:18.480 --> 23:20.816
No matter what, we'll get through it together,

23:20.899 --> 23:23.193
like peanut butter and jelly.

23:23.276 --> 23:24.277
[♪♪♪]

23:24.361 --> 23:28.198
Like pinot noir and Brussels sprouts.

23:28.281 --> 23:31.535
-Oh, we are so meant to be together.
-I know.

23:34.538 --> 23:36.706
KEVIN:
So the dumbest thing that I ever did,

23:36.790 --> 23:39.334
and you need to promise not to laugh,
but when I was 5,

23:39.417 --> 23:42.963
I broke my arm because I jumped off the roof.

23:43.046 --> 23:44.506
Why did you do that?

23:44.589 --> 23:48.176
Well, I was dressed as Superman.
I thought maybe I could fly.

23:48.260 --> 23:50.470
-Did you learn your lesson?
-The second time.

23:51.596 --> 23:54.307
-You promised you weren't gonna laugh.
-No, it's just funny.

23:54.391 --> 23:58.061
When I was 5, I tried to save a snowman
from jumping off our roof.

23:58.145 --> 23:59.855
-Jumping?
-Mm-hm. Yeah.

23:59.938 --> 24:03.108
Paulie and Joe spent an entire day
building this snowman on our roof,

24:03.191 --> 24:06.111
and then brought me outside
and told me I had to save him.

24:06.194 --> 24:07.195
Did you?

24:07.279 --> 24:12.242
I spent the entire evening dragging out
the couch cushions to break his fall.

24:12.325 --> 24:15.579
But the best part was the next morning,
Christmas day.

24:15.662 --> 24:18.915
We were in our matching onesies
and reindeer antlers,

24:18.999 --> 24:22.544
opening Christmas presents
while sitting on wet cushions.

24:22.627 --> 24:26.214
Let's go back for a second.
Matching onesies and reindeer antlers?

24:26.298 --> 24:27.507
Always. Every Christmas.

24:27.591 --> 24:29.092
[SARAH CHUCKLES]

24:29.176 --> 24:31.136
-That sounds fun.
-Yeah, it was.

24:31.219 --> 24:33.013
[PAGERS BEEPING]

24:33.096 --> 24:34.806
Paramedics and engines, everyone.

24:34.890 --> 24:37.225
[♪♪♪]

24:40.604 --> 24:42.147
Five minutes?

24:42.230 --> 24:44.482
Yeah. They don't know the start time.

24:48.028 --> 24:51.406
ABBY: So how'd the kids do on their test?
-Ah, pretty well,

24:51.489 --> 24:55.202
until two of my students thought
that Benjamin Franklin invented the kite.

24:55.285 --> 24:57.537
Well, I mean, it's close.

24:57.621 --> 25:00.540
That's true.
Yeah, maybe I can give them half credit.

25:00.624 --> 25:03.668
But more importantly, how'd it go for you?

25:04.252 --> 25:08.673
Oh. Well, like a kite in a storm.

25:08.757 --> 25:10.759
At first, it was reasonable, then it wasn't.

25:10.842 --> 25:13.803
And then they wanted me to take a deal,
which I didn't.

25:13.887 --> 25:15.680
Then they threatened me.

25:16.389 --> 25:17.307
Wow.

25:17.390 --> 25:20.143
-How'd that go?
-Uh...

25:20.227 --> 25:21.895
I don't know, I left.

25:22.395 --> 25:23.813
-Wow.
-Yeah.

25:24.898 --> 25:27.692
So, what's your position on picnics?

25:28.568 --> 25:30.737
-Uh, generally favorable.
-Good.

25:30.820 --> 25:34.574
Good. Warm day, soft blanket. Could be worse.

25:34.658 --> 25:35.492
It could be.

25:37.661 --> 25:42.082
You know, it's so funny, I just--
I realized that I like my job,

25:42.165 --> 25:45.293
but I would be okay without it.

25:46.795 --> 25:49.172
Then I think I've made a huge mistake
and I'll regret it,

25:49.256 --> 25:51.174
and what have I done and I'm gonna miss it...

25:52.467 --> 25:55.762
So, what's wrong with that?
It's normal to think about what might've been.

25:56.429 --> 25:58.139
You know, leaving what you know.

25:59.057 --> 26:03.561
You know, if it makes you feel any better,
and you promise not to tell anybody,

26:03.645 --> 26:06.856
I still count fish every time I watch <i>Finding Nemo.</i>

26:06.940 --> 26:09.609
-You've watched <i>Finding Nemo </i> more than once?
-Mm-hm.

26:09.693 --> 26:12.153
-You know, I do teach third grade.
-Yes.

26:12.237 --> 26:13.446
Oh. Ahem.

26:14.489 --> 26:18.243
Uh, I'm not sure that this is a juice-box moment.

26:18.326 --> 26:20.161
Well, I didn't think it was either.

26:24.291 --> 26:26.584
-Here you go.
-Thank you.

26:26.668 --> 26:28.712
-All right.
-Wow, so fancy.

26:28.795 --> 26:29.713
Mm-hm.

26:30.380 --> 26:32.757
It's better than Chateau Berry Blast.

26:32.841 --> 26:35.427
-I like Berry Blast.
-Yeah, it's not too bad.

26:38.179 --> 26:39.014
All right.

26:40.098 --> 26:41.433
-Cheers.
-Cheers.

26:41.975 --> 26:44.477
[♪♪♪]

26:48.481 --> 26:51.693
-This is nice.
-It is, isn't it?

27:02.912 --> 27:04.080
Thanks for meeting with me.

27:04.164 --> 27:07.792
I thought it'd be a good time to talk
and clear the air.

27:07.876 --> 27:10.670
Look, I'm sorry for coming down
on you like that, Mick.

27:10.754 --> 27:15.216
I know you're dealing with a lot,
it's just, you know, I really need you involved.

27:15.300 --> 27:16.217
I know, I know.

27:16.301 --> 27:18.345
And as soon as all this stuff with me blows over,

27:18.428 --> 27:21.056
I'm gonna make it a priority, I promise.

27:21.139 --> 27:22.557
You don't know when that's gonna be.

27:23.683 --> 27:27.187
Look, I've been thinking.
There's always another option.

27:28.438 --> 27:31.608
-What's that?
-You sell me your half of the club.

27:33.068 --> 27:36.071
I'd be happy to pay you full market value.

27:36.154 --> 27:38.656
You wanna buy me out? Why now?

27:39.741 --> 27:42.535
Because the Bridge means
something to me, Mick.

27:42.619 --> 27:45.038
It's always been my dream, not yours.

27:45.121 --> 27:47.123
I'll always appreciate what you did to help me,

27:47.207 --> 27:50.210
but I'm giving you an out, if you want it.

27:51.336 --> 27:52.420
If I want it?

27:53.088 --> 27:55.215
[♪♪♪]

27:56.841 --> 27:59.594
-Let me think about it.
-All right, great.

28:03.598 --> 28:05.600
[♪♪♪]

28:13.483 --> 28:17.695
Well, judging from that smile,
it looks like the deposition went well.

28:17.779 --> 28:21.241
Uh, it was great. Until I walked out.

28:22.450 --> 28:24.327
But I think I've made the right choice,

28:24.411 --> 28:27.664
although I might have sent myself
into an early retirement.

28:27.747 --> 28:29.332
So, what's the plan now?

28:29.416 --> 28:30.458
Actually,

28:30.542 --> 28:33.586
I was hoping that you could take me
and the girls sailing this weekend.

28:33.670 --> 28:35.130
God, honey, I'd love nothing more,

28:35.213 --> 28:38.466
but this Dilpher thing has got me
landlocked for a while.

28:38.550 --> 28:40.176
Mm. Right.

28:40.260 --> 28:41.845
Well, maybe you need a deposition

28:41.928 --> 28:44.472
to clear your schedule and change your life.

28:44.556 --> 28:48.059
Well, I'm not sure that's what they're for,
but I'll try it.

28:50.228 --> 28:51.229
[MICK CLEARS THROAT]

28:56.609 --> 28:58.445
Are these your notes on my stuff?

28:58.903 --> 29:01.740
Oh, yeah, they're just scribbles.
I couldn't help myself.

29:02.907 --> 29:05.410
I never thought about reapplying
for government exemptions

29:05.493 --> 29:07.162
to mitigate construction overages.

29:07.245 --> 29:08.830
-Really?
-Yeah.

29:08.913 --> 29:11.750
Well, for three years in New York, I handled most

29:11.833 --> 29:14.502
of the real estate investment trusts
for Capital Management.

29:14.586 --> 29:15.420
Huh.

29:16.546 --> 29:19.090
Abby, I've got multiple MBAs working for me

29:19.174 --> 29:22.260
and not one of them's ever come up with this.

29:22.343 --> 29:26.347
Well, I had a lot of time with nothing to do, so...

29:29.934 --> 29:34.022
You know, Nelson left me the boat
to remind me of what's important.

29:34.105 --> 29:36.608
I've been so focused on trying
to handle everything myself,

29:36.691 --> 29:40.737
I think I... I've forgotten what all this is about.

29:40.820 --> 29:41.780
What do you mean?

29:41.863 --> 29:46.242
Well, if you have some time,
I could use some help.

29:46.326 --> 29:49.204
With everything that's been going on,
I need somebody I can trust

29:49.287 --> 29:52.916
to handle the day-to-day
and everything that I can't handle.

29:52.999 --> 29:55.460
-It would just be temporary.
-Oh, Dad.

29:55.543 --> 29:58.296
Dad, of course. I mean, whatever you need.

29:58.379 --> 30:00.089
-Really?
-Yeah.

30:00.173 --> 30:01.341
Thanks.

30:01.424 --> 30:03.843
-It'll cost you babysitting, though.
-Okay.

30:04.844 --> 30:06.846
[BAND PLAYING ROCK MUSIC]

30:07.972 --> 30:11.142
I think you're the only O'Brien
that still comes here on a regular basis.

30:11.226 --> 30:13.353
Well, couldn't live without the hot wings.

30:14.604 --> 30:16.272
Is Danielle coming to meet you?

30:17.607 --> 30:18.900
No, we, uh...

30:20.777 --> 30:21.611
It's over.

30:22.695 --> 30:26.157
-Really? Sorry to hear that.
-Yeah.

30:27.534 --> 30:30.703
-So, what are you working on?
-Oh, the same old stuff.

30:30.787 --> 30:33.581
Just catching up on some research
for Uncle Thomas.

30:33.665 --> 30:36.876
Spending a lot of time doing work for Abby,
whether or not she'll use it.

30:36.960 --> 30:39.295
For Abby? Why would she need a lawyer?

30:40.046 --> 30:41.422
Because of the Porter Fund.

30:42.382 --> 30:43.591
Wait, that was her?

30:45.426 --> 30:48.471
-Wow. If I'd known, I would've...
-No, no, hey, hey, hey.

30:48.555 --> 30:51.182
It's okay. It's Abby, she always figures it out.

30:51.850 --> 30:55.979
You know, she's got, uh...
She's got people to talk to.

30:57.730 --> 30:59.357
Well, that's good.

31:00.358 --> 31:02.569
I'd hate to think Abby didn't have
the support she needed.

31:05.321 --> 31:06.656
Hey, Connor.

31:06.739 --> 31:07.657
Yeah?

31:07.740 --> 31:11.286
For what it's worth, you got great instincts.

31:11.369 --> 31:15.415
Anyone would be lucky
to have you on their side. I know I am.

31:17.333 --> 31:18.585
Thanks, Trace.

31:25.383 --> 31:26.801
All done.

31:26.885 --> 31:31.764
Scones, muffins, wine,
and two cheese platters ready for tonight.

31:31.848 --> 31:35.602
Gran, you are a lifesaver. How did you do it?

31:35.685 --> 31:38.354
I cranked up my oxygen.

31:38.438 --> 31:42.150
And I would do anything for you.

31:42.233 --> 31:44.569
-You always have.
-And I always will.

31:44.652 --> 31:45.570
Mmm.

31:46.738 --> 31:50.325
I wanted to ask you, um...

31:50.408 --> 31:54.913
-This whole Mom and Dad thing...
-Jess, Jess.

31:54.996 --> 31:57.498
I know there were times that you felt

31:57.582 --> 32:01.669
that your mother and your dad
weren't there for you.

32:01.753 --> 32:03.338
And you're right, they weren't.

32:03.421 --> 32:08.134
Because they knew that I would be
and that you would never be truly alone.

32:09.469 --> 32:14.182
-You're not worried it's gonna fall apart?
-No, I'm not, and you shouldn't be either.

32:14.265 --> 32:17.644
They're trying it now
because they feel safe to do it.

32:17.727 --> 32:20.480
And no matter what,
you kids are gonna all be okay.

32:20.563 --> 32:24.150
And, Jess, you are never going to be alone.

32:24.233 --> 32:25.276
[♪♪♪]

32:25.360 --> 32:26.653
I'll always have you.

32:26.736 --> 32:29.197
-And David.
-And David.

32:30.990 --> 32:31.908
Thank you.

32:37.038 --> 32:38.122
That's my daughter.

32:39.207 --> 32:44.545
There you go, and that includes
your 10 percent off. Thank you.

32:44.629 --> 32:48.925
Hi. Uh, Mom, what are you doing here?
And why are we having a sale?

32:49.008 --> 32:50.802
Kevin called, and he and Sarah had to leave,

32:50.885 --> 32:53.888
and I was thinking
I could help you move up the bestseller list.

32:53.972 --> 32:56.057
-Sign these, please.
-Oh.

32:57.058 --> 32:59.477
-That's actually not a bad idea.
-Thank you.

32:59.560 --> 33:00.812
How was Baltimore?

33:01.479 --> 33:05.441
Not great. Turns out I'm not very good
at talking about myself.

33:05.525 --> 33:06.442
Oh, honey.

33:06.526 --> 33:10.071
When I write, it's always about the old me.

33:10.738 --> 33:12.365
It's never about who I am now.

33:12.448 --> 33:13.700
Hm.

33:13.783 --> 33:15.827
Well, then, who are you now?

33:16.619 --> 33:17.453
Huh.

33:17.537 --> 33:19.747
[♪♪♪]

33:19.831 --> 33:21.165
That is the question.

33:28.798 --> 33:30.508
You okay?

33:30.591 --> 33:35.013
-Yeah. Yeah, I'm just tired.
-Yeah, me too.

33:37.432 --> 33:41.978
-You ever think about how we got here?
-Yeah, I do.

33:42.437 --> 33:46.107
There was a long time
where I thought I'd never be happy again.

33:46.190 --> 33:47.734
I didn't even think it'd be possible.

33:51.154 --> 33:54.574
My dad always used to say
that we all live two lives.

33:54.657 --> 33:57.201
One to learn, and one to live.

33:59.370 --> 34:01.414
I think I'm good with the football team.

34:02.707 --> 34:06.794
-Just the offense?
-Offense, defense, water boys.

34:06.878 --> 34:09.547
Okay, heh, now you're scaring me.

34:14.342 --> 34:16.471
CONNOR:
Gran? You home?

34:17.972 --> 34:19.974
-Hey, Abby.
-Hey.

34:20.058 --> 34:22.393
Uh, is Gran here?

34:22.476 --> 34:25.730
Uh, no, she went to Sally's with Dad
before the play.

34:25.813 --> 34:26.938
Ah.

34:27.023 --> 34:28.608
How'd your deposition go?

34:29.442 --> 34:32.904
Well, I used the research you gave me
for the first hour.

34:32.987 --> 34:35.531
Well, I'm glad my hard work went to good use.

34:35.614 --> 34:40.703
Yes. Then I threw my career away
right after that. Don't ask.

34:41.704 --> 34:44.290
Fair enough. What are you working on?

34:44.373 --> 34:46.793
It's my consolation prize.
I'm just doing some work for Dad.

34:48.293 --> 34:50.379
Really? Working for Dad?

34:50.838 --> 34:53.174
Just for the moment. He just asked me
to help him out with some stuff.

34:53.257 --> 34:54.217
Huh.

34:54.300 --> 34:55.842
[♪♪♪]

34:55.927 --> 35:00.223
-When did he ask you?
-Mmm. I don't know. A few hours ago.

35:04.936 --> 35:05.770
Hm.

35:07.939 --> 35:09.941
[♪♪♪]

35:12.360 --> 35:15.029
Connor, with all due respect,
what are you doing here?

35:15.113 --> 35:16.823
I'm going home.

35:16.906 --> 35:18.616
You offered me a job.

35:18.699 --> 35:20.326
That's not good enough.

35:20.409 --> 35:21.953
And you need me.

35:22.036 --> 35:23.037
And why is that?

35:23.121 --> 35:27.208
Because I single-handedly beat your law firm
in a case that I had no right to win.

35:28.042 --> 35:30.920
You need me because I'm smart, I'm aggressive...

35:31.003 --> 35:32.004
Humble.

35:33.005 --> 35:37.844
When necessary. And you need me
because I can help you and your firm.

35:38.261 --> 35:42.014
But while we do some environmental law,
mostly we do litigation.

35:42.098 --> 35:45.268
And that's exactly why I got into law
in the first place.

35:45.351 --> 35:47.353
Fine. I'm interested.

35:49.897 --> 35:55.695
So how did you end up
going into environmental law?

35:55.778 --> 35:56.612
Well...

35:58.406 --> 36:03.119
I let others choose my path for me.
And I'm done doing that.

36:04.203 --> 36:05.079
Hmm.

36:10.751 --> 36:13.588
We lost this case to the city.

36:13.671 --> 36:16.549
You have 48 hours to show me
how we could have won it.

36:17.633 --> 36:20.219
You want me to dazzle you?

36:21.345 --> 36:22.430
If you want a job.

36:22.513 --> 36:24.515
[♪♪♪]

36:34.650 --> 36:38.487
-I think your break's almost over.
-Can I get five more minutes, boss?

36:38.571 --> 36:40.740
It's not how it works. Gonna have to dock you.

36:47.288 --> 36:49.707
You know, I don't let a lot of people in.

36:49.790 --> 36:54.170
-So no one knows the real Trace Riley?
-Not a lot of people, no.

36:55.838 --> 36:59.926
-Because of the business?
-Not just that.

37:00.009 --> 37:03.554
When I was a kid, my family wasn't big
on discussing their feelings.

37:04.597 --> 37:06.724
Sometimes it's just easier that way.

37:06.807 --> 37:08.351
So you don't get hurt.

37:08.434 --> 37:12.063
So you get hurt less. It's, uh, safer.

37:15.316 --> 37:19.362
You know, you don't have
to protect yourself around me.

37:19.445 --> 37:20.821
[♪♪♪]

37:20.905 --> 37:22.782
You don't have to hide how you really feel.

37:27.328 --> 37:29.288
KEVIN:
Your ride awaits.

37:29.372 --> 37:31.332
-You all set to leave?
-Almost.

37:31.415 --> 37:34.210
Just finishing this note from the playwright.

37:34.293 --> 37:37.213
So you finally found out
what the real you has to say.

37:37.296 --> 37:38.297
Uh...

37:39.507 --> 37:42.677
Yeah, kind of, I guess. Not really.

37:42.760 --> 37:44.887
I did find out why I was stressing out, though.

37:44.971 --> 37:48.099
It's because I have nothing to stress out about.

37:49.392 --> 37:52.228
Yeah, that's strange, having everything work out.

37:53.479 --> 37:58.567
Sarah and I are just happy,
planning our future together,

37:58.651 --> 38:00.945
our wedding dinner, everything else.

38:01.570 --> 38:04.031
And I keep expecting that I'm gonna wake up.

38:04.115 --> 38:07.576
-I know, right? Like it's all just a dream.
-Yeah, that it won't last.

38:09.829 --> 38:11.330
But then I think...

38:12.957 --> 38:15.584
maybe we deserve this.

38:17.086 --> 38:22.967
You know, like, for just a moment,
everything's good.

38:23.050 --> 38:25.344
And everything works out as we planned.

38:25.428 --> 38:26.804
[♪♪♪]

38:31.767 --> 38:34.270
Well, we got through the day.

38:34.353 --> 38:35.563
[ELECTRICITY CRACKLES]

38:37.189 --> 38:40.860
-And tomorrow will be better.
-Always is.

38:40.943 --> 38:42.987
That reminds me, I got you a present.

38:43.612 --> 38:46.365
-Really?
-It's okay if you didn't get me anything.

38:46.449 --> 38:48.993
Even though it was the first day
and you should've, but--

38:49.076 --> 38:50.703
-I'm kidding. Close your eyes.
-Now?

38:50.786 --> 38:51.620
Mm-hm.

38:54.332 --> 38:56.709
-Okay.
-Aww, a calendar.

38:56.792 --> 39:00.087
So we will always know what day it is.

39:00.171 --> 39:03.382
This would've been a lot more useful
than a spice rack.

39:03.466 --> 39:04.508
[♪♪♪]

39:04.592 --> 39:06.552
It's okay, you don't have to get me anything.

39:07.887 --> 39:09.221
-Got it.
-Got it.

39:33.287 --> 39:35.081
Are you all right?

39:35.164 --> 39:38.793
I've been better. Hasn't been
a great month for my reputation.

39:38.876 --> 39:40.586
Yeah, well, it's really difficult

39:40.669 --> 39:44.465
to see something
that you've built up just fall apart.

39:44.548 --> 39:45.383
Oh-ho.

39:48.010 --> 39:52.431
You know, I talked to Jess today.

39:52.515 --> 39:56.102
And she is very concerned about you and Megan.

39:57.186 --> 39:58.646
Oh?

39:58.729 --> 40:00.439
Yeah.

40:00.523 --> 40:01.857
How do you feel about it?

40:01.941 --> 40:06.946
Well, I think you've always had something special.

40:07.029 --> 40:08.656
And I want you to be happy.

40:08.739 --> 40:10.741
[♪♪♪]

40:10.825 --> 40:12.076
Thank you, Mom.

40:15.579 --> 40:18.124
Admiral? What course will we be taking?

40:18.207 --> 40:22.002
It be morning soon, so we point the bow
toward the rising sun.

40:22.086 --> 40:25.005
CAITLYN: Aye, aye, admiral.
But what if there not be land?

40:25.089 --> 40:27.633
CARRIE: Then we'll be setting a new course.
-That's you. Let's go.

40:27.716 --> 40:29.593
CAITLYN:
Time to abandon hope.

40:29.677 --> 40:32.263
Trace. What are you doing here?

40:32.346 --> 40:34.181
I told the girls I'd come by and help out.

40:35.474 --> 40:36.725
Oh, um...

40:37.810 --> 40:41.480
Thank you for, um, building the sets.
They look better than the originals.

40:42.565 --> 40:43.774
Yeah, no worries.

40:45.693 --> 40:47.486
You know, I heard about the Porter Fund.

40:48.821 --> 40:52.283
-You okay?
-Yeah, yeah, I'm better now.

40:52.950 --> 40:53.993
Good.

40:54.076 --> 40:56.162
[AUDIENCE APPLAUDING AND CHEERING]

40:56.245 --> 40:58.122
I, um... Heh-heh.

40:58.205 --> 41:01.000
I have to go do a, uh, costume change.

41:01.083 --> 41:02.376
Yeah, yeah, sure.

41:03.752 --> 41:05.754
[♪♪♪]

41:22.021 --> 41:24.023
[♪♪♪]

44:06.018 --> 44:08.312
NARRATOR:
<i>Next week on </i> Chesapeake Shores:

44:08.395 --> 44:11.732
-There's a timing for everything, Mick.
-Yeah, including when to retaliate.

44:11.815 --> 44:13.859
As of today, I'm firing back.

44:13.942 --> 44:17.988
According to our records, your occupancy permit
didn't go into effect until yesterday.

44:18.072 --> 44:19.823
BREE:
You're getting engaged?

44:19.907 --> 44:23.452
HANNAH: My agent wanted to meet you.
-Brian Higgins. We should do lunch.

44:23.911 --> 44:25.954
So that's her.

44:26.038 --> 44:29.124
-You still have feelings for her, don't you?
-It's not that simple.

44:29.500 --> 44:32.336
Trace, I, um...

44:32.419 --> 44:33.629
have to go.

